{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6c427ce1-3efd-4f01-b55e-da461e4f3e74","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/   # your own crashes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/    # system-wide crashes\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**Other options:**\n- Open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n- If you have a connected iOS device, crash logs appear in `~/Library/Logs/CrashReporter/MobileDevice/`\n\nOnce you have the `.ips` file, you can symbolicate the .NET runtime frames to get function names and source lines. Want help with that?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"45f1dfa8-28e7-4ad4-81c2-43c9fa488f78","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting — I can answer directly.","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"D801:96055:1B9EA0:209074:69F2B52F"},"id":"5b7fa74f-a41e-4bdc-97da-745a6093b121","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:49:43.540Z","parentId":"6d028ae1-6bc3-4581-acc0-3a8dae625936"}
